From Figure 5, the trend that should be most apparent is the proportion of beef and buffalo being consumed compared to the proportion of poultry that is being consumed. Not only has consumption of beef and buffalo decreased until 2021 but it is also expected to decrease even more by 2050! On the other hand, the proportion of poultry has been increasing and is predicted to continue increasing as well. One of the reasons this is the case is because of the concerns about the consumption of too much â€œred meat.â€ This group of meat includes beef, goat and pork. These types of meat have greater amounts of saturated fats and bad cholesterol, both which if consumed too often can increase the risks of type 2 diabetes, stroke and colorectal cancer. From Figure 4, we recall that cattle was one of the largest polluters of methane whereas poultry was amongst the least so this trend that we are seeing is a positive sign for our future because by decreasing demand for animals such as cattle and increasing demand for poultry will decrease greenhouse gas emissions globally. Our suggested alternative to agricultural meat is to begin consuming plant-based meat! Figure 6 considers what would happen when switching over to plant-based meat. Plant-based is considered a substitute for traditional meat because of how similar it tastes to their meat counterpart. This visualization shows the percentage of greenhouse gasses that are emitted by the plant-based versions of some of your favorite burgers. The most significant reduction of greenhouse gasses comes from consuming a plant-based beef burger as opposed to a regular beef burger. The percentages are not as high when considering other meats such as chicken and pork but we have to remember, these animals released very little greenhouse gasses into our atmosphere in the first place! Save the world by switching to these great tasting alternatives.
